{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/anonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea", "time": 1683005883.393582, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/anonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Anonymous Functions in Python. Introduction to Lambda Expressions | by Sadrach Pierre, Ph.D. | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Anonymous Functions in Python", "description": "Defining functions is a significant part of software programming. One way to define a simple function is anonymously using a lambda expression. For example, a function that evaluates a single\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://d.cxcore.net/Python/Python_Cookbook_3rd_Edition.pdf", "anchor_text": "The Python Cookbook", "paragraph_index": 15}, {"url": "https://github.com/spierre91/medium_code/blob/master/basic_python/lambda_expressions.py", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["Defining functions is a significant part of software programming. One way to define a simple function is anonymously using a lambda expression. For example, a function that evaluates a single expression, like addition, can be replaced with a lambda expression. In this post, we will discuss how to define anonymous/inline functions using lambda expressions.", "Suppose we have a one-line function that returns the difference between two input integer values:", "If we call this function with x= 10 and y =7, and print the return value we get:", "Since this is a simple function that does nothing more than evaluate a single expression, \u201cx-y\u201d, it can be replaced with a lambda expression:", "The lambda expression contains the keyword \u201clambda\u201d, the inputs x and y, a colon, and the expression we want to evaluate. If we look back to our original function definition:", "We see that these expressions look pretty similar. The biggest difference is the absence of the \u2018def\u2019 keyword, \u2018return\u2019 keyword and function name in our lambda expression.", "Let\u2019s print the function with x = 10 and y = 7 as inputs:", "You can apply lambda expressions to more interesting operations such as sorting and data reduction. Let\u2019s consider the following list of programming language creators:", "We can use the \u2018sorted()\u2019 method along with a lambda expression to return the list in alphabetical order by last name:", "It is worth noting the limitations of lambda expressions. Since we can only evaluate single expressions, features like iteration, exception handling, and conditionals can\u2019t be specified. Despite this, lambda expressions are very useful in place of one-line functions that evaluate single expressions.", "Another thing we can consider is how to capture variables in anonymous functions. Let\u2019s define an integer x = 5, and define an anonymous function that adds x and another input integer, y:", "Let\u2019s call our function with y = 24:", "If we change the value of x in the next line and call our function, we get:", "Since the x used in the lambda expression is a free variable bound at runtime, the value of x is whatever it is at runtime. To have anonymous functions capture a value at the point of definition, in this case capture x = 5, we must include x as default value:", "We get the behavior we desired. I\u2019ll stop here but I encourage you to play around with the code yourself.", "To summarize, in this post we discussed how to define anonymous functions in python using lambda expressions. If you have a python script containing many functions that evaluate one-line expressions, it is often easier to replace these functions with lambda expressions. Further, we discussed how to set a default value in our lambda expression, which allowed us to capture the value of a variable at the point of definition. If you wish you learn more about anonymous functions, I recommend reading The Python Cookbook. I hope you found this post interesting/useful. The code in this post is available on GitHub. Thank you for reading!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Writer for Built In & Towards Data Science. Cornell University Ph. D. in Chemical Physics."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F914a0a4b86ea&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fanonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fanonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fanonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fanonymous-functions-in-python-914a0a4b86ea&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://to